"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69027"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA liver biopsy specimen is obtained from a patient with suspected fatty liver disease. Microscopic examination reveals numerous clear, round vacuoles within hepatocytes. These vacuoles displace the cell nuclei to the periphery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological pattern shown in this liver specimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Steatosis","Steatofibrosis","Glycogenosis","Haemosiderosis","Cholestasis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological pattern described shows \u003Cstrong\u003Esteatosis\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by accumulation of fat droplets within hepatocytes. These appear as clear, round vacuoles that displace the nucleus to the cell periphery, creating a characteristic \u0027signet ring\u0027 appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect patterns can be distinguished:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESteatofibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E shows collagen deposition and architectural distortion in addition to fat accumulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycogenosis\u003C/strong\u003E shows pale, granular cytoplasm without distinct vacuoles\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemosiderosis\u003C/strong\u003E shows golden-brown granular deposits of iron within hepatocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholestasis\u003C/strong\u003E shows green-brown bile pigment accumulation within hepatocytes and canaliculi\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESteatosis represents the earliest stage of fatty liver disease, which can progress to steatohepatitis (with inflammation) and eventually fibrosis if untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatic steatosis is characterised by clear, round fat vacuoles within hepatocytes that displace nuclei peripherally.","Fatty liver disease progresses from simple steatosis to steatohepatitis to fibrosis.","Key histological features distinguish steatosis from other hepatic conditions like glycogenosis, haemosiderosis and cholestasis."],"references":["Torbenson M, Washington K. Pathology of liver disease: advances in the last 50 years. Hum Pathol. 2020 Jan;95:78-98. doi: 10.1016/j.humpath.2019.08.023. Epub 2019 Sep 4. PMID: 31493428","Chan WK, Chuah KH, Rajaram RB, Lim LL, Ratnasingam J, Vethakkan SR. Metabolic Dysfunction-Associated Steatotic Liver Disease (MASLD): A State-of-the-Art Review. J Obes Metab Syndr. 2023 Sep 30;32(3):197-213. doi: 10.7570/jomes23052. Epub 2023 Sep 13. PMID: 37700494; PMCID: PMC10583766","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","\u0022Steatohepatitis high mag\u0022 by Nephron is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Steatohepatitis_high_mag.jpg"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54484"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15298"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21152"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.